{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_protoss_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280656306/1908061401/0127.xml":{"full_text":"FINANCE\nMARKI\nSome Uneasiness Marked the\nWek-End Dealings.\nFIRMNESS BEFORE CLOSE\nHew IT. P. Bond Quotation Corrected\nFirst Impression.\nSTEEL REPORTS WERE GOOD\nBank Statement Supplied No Surprises?Fine\nCash Cain Shown.\nLoan Expansion Expected.\nNEW YORK. June 13 ?There was some\nrenewal of uneasiness among speculative\nholders of stocks today, which prompted\nthe throwing over of holdings yesterday\non account of the funding Erie bond\ncoupons and the closing of subscriptions j\nfor the Union Pacific bonds. A tone of\ngreater assurance developed before the\nmarket closed. London was markedly displeased\nwith the Erie incident, and continued\nto sell those securities freely.\nThe new Union Pacific bonds were admitted\nto quotation on the stock exchange\n\"when issued.\" and dealings in\nthe bonds on that basis at 05^. the subscription\nprice, and above, had an effect\nin correcting the unfavorable impression\nmade by yesterday's decline below the\nsubscription price.\nBankers who underwrote the bonds\nstated that small bidders would receive\nthe full amount applied for. while larger\napplicants would receive 60 per cent of\nthe bids, the amount apportioned to the\nrespective classes, however, not being\nstated. Neither was the amount of foreign\nsubscription stated.\nT* woe inforroH that enma of th^ hifl- I\nV tl UU tillt.1 I VW W U V\nders had made overapplications in the\nexpectation that full allotments would\ngot be made and were sellers at the decline\nto P5 when they learned the exter\nof the bonds which would be allotted to\nthem.\nU. P. Overapplications.\nThe precedent of the Pennsylvania\nbond subscription, when applicants received\nonly 5 per cent of the amounts bid\nfor and small bids were thrown out altogether.\nseems to have influenced the overapplications\nin this case, which, however,\nmet with no such active competition as\nin the case of the Pennsylvania issue.\nReports of large resumptions among\neteel mills helped to steady stocks and\nmoderate improvement in mercantile lines\nreported by the commercial agencies had\na good influence. The shading of the\nUnion Pacific bonds to below the subscription\nprice again late in the dealings\ncaused a hesitating movement in the\nrally, but the market closed steady.\nThe bank statement supplied no surprises.\nThe cash accretion was,fully re\nnectea in me statement 01 actual conditions\nand other banks showed a handsome\ncash gain as well. The loan expansion\nwas expected in view of the\nweek's financial transactions.\nBonds were steady. Total sales, par\nvalue, $1,299,000, U. S. 2s advanced Mi\nand the 4s registered Per cent on call\nduring the week.\nNew York Closing Stock List.\nNSW YORK. June 13.\n,?Sales.?, Clo6'g\nHifb. Low. Bid.\nAmalgamated Copper... 17% 65% 67%\nAmerican Car A Foundry iM 34 34\nAmerican Cat A Foundry pfd. 96-98%\nAmerican Cotton Oil 30% 30% 30%\nAmerican Hide A Leather pfd IS 18 17\nAmerican Ice Securities 16% 2d US'*\nAmerican Linseed 9%\nAmerican Locomotive 48% 48% 48\nAmerican Locomotive pfd i<>3 102 101\nAmerican Sinelt'g Reflu'g.. 73% 74 75\nAmerican Smelt. A Refln. pfd t'T% 97% 98\nAmerican Sugar Refining 120% 126 1S?%\nAmerican Tobacco pf<l 90%\nAmerican Woolen 22\nAnaconda Mining Co -2% 41% 42%\nAtcUlaon 81% 79% 80%\nAtchison pfd H3% 93% 93%\nAtlantic Coast Line 9o\nBaltimore A- Ohio el) 88% 87% J\nBaltimore A Ohio pfd 83-87 i\nBmidrln. D.nlH Tr.n,ll 17 1KU _ll!7.\nw?u ???I'ivi a auai ii\nCanadian Pacific 158% 158 158%\nCentral Leather 25 24% 25\nCentral Leather pfd 05\nCertral of New Jersey 181-85\nChesapeake ft Ohio 44** 43% 44\nChicago Great Western 0%\nChicago 4k Northwestern 150 150 150\nChicago, MIL St. Paul 133 131}* 132**\nC., C-. C. ft St. Louis... 50%\nColorado Fuel 4k Iron 2d 20 20%\nColorado ft Southern tin** 30% SO;**\nColorado ft Southern 1st pfd. 58 58 58\nColorado ft Southern 2d pfd.. 49% 49% 49%\nConsolidated Gas. 121% 121% 121%\nCom Products 10 10 15%\nDelaware ft Hudson 158% 158% 158%\nlienver ft Kio tirande 25-% 25% 25\nDenver ft Bio Grande pfd 03 00\nDistillers' Securities 53% 33% 3-';%\nErie I.* lS-% 18%\nErie 1st pfd 30 33% 35\nErie 2d pfd 23% 23% 24\nOeneral Electric 134 134 134\nGieat Northern pfd 30% 129% 130%\nGreat Northern Ore ctfs 59% 59% 59%\nIllinois Central 12!'% 129% 129%\nInterborough-Metropolitan 10% 10% 10%\nInterborougli-Metropolltan pfd 28% 27% 28%\nInrernationai Paper 10 9% 9-%\nInternational Paper pfd 55-58\nInternational Pump 23\nlow* Central 10% 10% 10%\nKansas City Southern 34 34 23%\nKansas City Southern pfd 55%\nLouisville ft Nashville 107% 107% 107%\nMexican Central 15-%\nMlnnea|>oila ft St. Louis 27% 27% 27\nMinn.. St. P. ft S. Ste. M... lil% llu 110\nMissouri Pacific 17*j 40% 47\nMissouri. Kansas ft Texas.... 20% 20% 27\nMissouri. Kansas ft Texas pfd 00%\nNational Lead C5% 04% 05%\nNew York Central 104% 104 104\nNew Y'ork, Ontario ft Weat 39%\nNorfolk ft Western 09 08% 08%\nNorth American uo 00 59%\nNorthern Pacific 130% 134% 130\nPaciflc Mall 23 24% 24*-,\nPennsylvania 121 12b% 120%\nPfoplf'i Oas 01\nPittsburg. C-. f. St. Louis 72-73\nPressed Steel Car 2b% 23% 2*1\nI oilman l a lace Car 13*\nRailway Steel Spring 3*1%\nReading 112% 110i* H2*\nRepublic Steel...'. is lh 17%\nRepublic Steel pfd to1* W>% th>%\nRock laland Co 17 ltr\\ 17\nRock Island Co. pfd .\".HVa 32% 33%\nSt. Louis fc Sau 1'ran. 2d pfd 27% 27% 27%\nSt. Ixiuis Southwestern 13%\nSt. Louis Southwestern pfd ?IO\nSloss-SUeffield Steel lrou.. 3o 7>o 4!i%\nSouthern Paciflc 84% 83%\nSouthern Pacific pfd J Its lib 118%\nSouthern Railway 17% 10% 17\nSouthern Railway l?fd 43% 43%\nTennessee Copper 3?>% 3?>% 33%\nTexas Paciflc 2:5%\nToledo, St. la.uls West.? 10% 10% 10%\nToledo. St. L. West. pfd... 41% 44% 43%\nUnion Paciflc 114% 142% 144%\nUnion Paciflc pfd ?2\nUnited States Rubber 23\nUnited States Rubber 1st pfd 02% 02% ?2%\nUnited States Steel i'7% .'hi'*. 3d7*.\nVnited states Steel pfd 1<?14 lul4 1014\nI'Uli Copper 31*4\nVirginia-i urollna Chemical ICS'Si\nVirginia-Carolina Cbein. pM.. 1<>0 iOf?\nWabash 11?, 11', in,\nWat*sli pM 33 23->? 23\nWeatinghouxe Ele< rrlc -i\"?4 4\"?4 46\nWestern Inlon.. 75% .Vi 54\nWheeling I.ake Erie t<\nWisconsin Central 17 17 164\nTotal tales for the day. l.S4.S?>0 shares.\nNew York Mining Stocks.\nNEW YORK. June 13.\ntile*. 2?f?\nBreeie 05\nBrunswick l oosolidated 10\n.\"ooiatock Tunnel Stock 33\nCouaMock Tunnel Bomla 173\nConsolidated California and Virginia 54\nHorn Silver SO\nLeadvlile Consolidated OS\nLittle Chief 05\nMexican: 65\nOntario 7315\nOphir 2tiO\nSmall Hope*. IK\nStandard 105\nYellow Jacket 60\nNew York Metal Market.\nNEW YORK. June 13?The metal markets\nwere quiet In the absence of cables\nand prices were nominally unchanged\nTin was dull at 28.2oa2^..'?:>. Copper 1:\nsteady in tone, with Lake quoted ai\n12.A7Hal3.00; electrolytic at 12 624al2.ST4\nand casting at 1230al2624 Lead war\ni quiet at 4.4~4a*-52H. and spelter dull a*\nL4.574a4 ?24. Iron remained quiet at re\ncent prices.\n\nTRADI\niTS OF TH\n\nTHE GRAIN MARKETS.\nCHICAGO, June 13.?Additional rain In\nKansas and Missouri was chiefly responsible\nfor a sharp bulge in the local wheat\nmarket today. At the close the July\ndelivery showed a net gain of 1%. Corn\nwas %aS4. Oats were higher and\nprovisions 2Va lower to 2Vi higher.\nThe wheat market opened strong owing\nto an active general demand, which was\nbrought out by the unfavorable weather\nconditions for the new crop in parts of\nthe winter wheat belt and by an advance\nof more than Id at Liverpool. Numerous\ncrop damage reports were received durin\nor frltA <^ov onH thAS^ tAndpd to Rdd to\n\"ft mc Uaj I w*t<4 vovwv _\nthe strength. There was liberal realizing\nat times, but offerings were readily\ntaken and the market showed no signs\nof weakening. The close was strong.\nJuly opened to higher, at 88% to\n89, advanced to 89%, and closed at 89%.\nClearances of wheat and flour were equal\nto 197,000 bushels. Primary receipts were\n236,000 bushels, compared with 411,?>i0\nbushels the corresponding day a year ago.\nMinneapolis. Duluth and Chicago reported\nreceipts of 111 cars, against 170 cars last\nweek and 275 cars a year ago.\nThe corn market was firm at the start\nbecause of the strength of wheat, but\nheavy sales based on more favorable\nweather conditions for the new crop soon\ncaused a severe slump in prices. The\nmarket was also bearishly affected by a\nsubstantial increase in local receipts. A\nheavy tone prevailed throughout the remainder\nof the day, and the market\nclosed weak at almost the lowest point.\nJuly opened ',4a% higher, at 67% to 67%,\nsold off to 66% and closed at 6rt%a66%.\nLocal receipts were 347 cars, with 52 of\ncontract grade.\nOats were firm all day, owing to the\nstrength of wheat and to some unfavorable\nnews regarding the new crop Trading\nwas fairly active early in the day.\nbut later became quiet. July openen\nto higher, at 43 to 43%. held within\nthat range, and closed at 43. Local receipts\nwere 130 cars.\nProvisions were quiet the greater part of\nthe day and the market was fairly steady.\nThe break in corn tended to offset a 5c to\n10c advance in live hogs. At the close\nJuly pork was up 2%c. at 14-12%. Lard\nwas off 2%c. at 8.75. Ribs were unchanged\nat 7.75.\nEstimated receipts for Monday: Wheat,\n17 cars; corn. 432 cars; oats, 111 cats;\nhogs, 43,000 head.\nST. LOUIS. June 13.?Wheat?No. 2 red\ncash, 95ai*>; No. 2 hard, 94al.00; July,\nlae^aSB^g; September, 84%.\nCorn?No. 2 cash. 72a72%; No. 2 white,\n78a78%; July, 67%a67%; September. 64%.\nOats?No. 2 cash. 52%; No. 2 white, 55;\nSeptember, 35%.\nMINNEAPOLIS. Minn., June 13.-Close:\nWheat. No. 1 hard, 1.10%; No. 1 northern,\n1.08%; July. 1.03; September 90.\nFlour?First patents, 5.30a545; second\npatents. 5.30a5.35; first clears, 4.2oa4.3t>;\nsecond clears. 3.50 a3.60.\nBran?In bulk, 18.50al9.G0.\nMILWAUKEE. Wis.. June 13?Wheat,\nNo. 1 northern, l.lOal.ll; No. 2 northern,\nl.G7al.09; July. 89% asked.\nRye?No. 1, 78%a79.\nBarley?No. 2. 60; sample. 4Sa55.\nCorn?No. 3 cash. 70a71; July, 66% bid.\n1TTIT T..ma 1 f> \\Ta\ni yibtin. ?unaiM uuuc iu.?uucai?\n1 hard, 1.10; No. 1 northern, 1.06; No. 2\nnorthern, 1.00%; July, 1.05%; September,\neovs.\nNew York Bonds.\nNEW YORK, June 13.\nXT. S. refunding 2s. registered 104\nXT. S. refunding 2s. coupon 10414\nI'. S. 3s, registered 101\nU. S. 3s, coupon 101\nU. S. 4s, registered 120%\nU. 8. 4s. coupon 122\nAmerican Tobacco 4s 72%\nAmerican Tobacco 6s 105%\nAtchison general 4s 08%\nAtchison adjustment 4s. bid 88\nAtchison eonv. 4s 80%\nAtchison conv. 5s..... 100%\nAtlantic Coast Line 4s....... 92%\nBaltimore A Ohio 4s 98%\nBaltimore Ohio 3%s 02%\nBrooklyn Rapid Transit conv. as 72\nCentral of Georgia 5s 105\nCentral of Georgia 1st inc., offered 71\nCentral of Georgia 2d inc., offered. 40%\nCentral of Georgia 3d inc 36%\nChesapeake Ohio 4%#..' 101\nChicago A Alton 3%s, bid 67\nChicago. Burlington A Quiney new 4s 96%\nChicago. Rock Island A Pacific R.R. 4s.t. 64\ntli lea go. Rock Island Pacific K.li. col.5s 70\nChicago. R. I. A Pacific By. rfdg. 4s 86%\nC.. C.. C. A St. Louis general 4s. bid 9.J_\nColorado Industrial 5s 60%\nColorado Midland 4?. bid 62%\nCole iilo A Southern 4s 89%\nDeis- ire A Hudson conv. 4s, offered 99%\nDenve.- Rio Grande 4b. bid 91%\nErie prior lien 4s 88\nErie general 4s 08%\nHocking Valley 4%s. bid 103%\nInterborougli Metropolitan 4%s 6.V.\nJapan 4a 80%\nJapan 4%a W-%\nJapan 4%s. 2d series 88%\nLouisville Nashville unified 4* 90\nManhattan consol gold 4b, bid 85%\nMexican Ventral 4?, bid 84%\nMexican Central 1st inc., bid 15\nMinneapolis St. Louis 4s 82\nMissouri. Kansas Texas 4b. bid 9?%\nMissouri. Kansas 4c Texas 2ds. bid ?3\nNational K.R. of Mexico consol la, bid... 81%\nNew York Central general 3%s 92%\nNew Jersey Central general 5s. bid..'. 123%\ni Northern Pacific 4s 101\ni Northern Pacific 3s. bid 71\n1 Norfolk Western consul 4s 645i\nOregon Short Line rfdg. 4s 90\nPennsylvania conv. 3%s. 1915 91%\nPennsylvania consol 4s 101',\nReading general 4s.. 98%\nRepublic of Cuba 5s. bid li?3\nst. I/nuis Iron Mountain consul 5s. offd. 1<*>%\nSt. Louis San Francisco funding 4s 72%\ni St. Louis Southwestern coo. 4s\nSeaboard Air Line 4s 52\nSouthern Pacific 4s 85%\nSouthern Pacific lsf 4s.. 92%\nSouthern Railway 5s. bid 98\nTexas Si Pacific lsts 104\nToledo. St. l?ul* Western 4s 73%\nI'nton Pacific 4s 102%\nUnion Pacific conv. 4s 91\nI\\ S. Steel 2d 5s 9ti% j\nWabash lsts, bid 53%\nWestern Maryland 4s. bid...\". Mt\n.rhaalln.. X. T ul/A re<A iu Kf/1 llQ\nurriju|? u i<in\nU'Isioiimd Central 4b. bid 85</a\nX. Y., X. H. H. conv. tte. ctfa 1S6V*\nBoston Stocks and Bonds.\nBOSTON\", June Id.\nMONEY. Clone.\nCall loans I',a2^\nTime loans 2Uta4la\nBONDS.\nAtchison adjustable 4*. bid A7\nAtchison 4s 07\nMexican Central 4a W\nRAILROADS.\nAtchison 80%\nAtchison ptd 92\nBoston A Albany 202\nB?st\" A Maine, bid 127\nI Be rn Elevated 132\ni Ki' ulmrp pfd.. bid 125\nNew York. New Haven A Hartford 125\nUnion Pacific 144Vi\nMISCELLANEOUS.\nAmerican Arge. Chemical pfd 85\nAmerican Pneumatic lube\nAmerican Sugar 12fi\nAmerican Sugar pfd 125\nAmerican Telegraph Telephone 118%\nAmerican Woolen 21%\nAmerican Woolen pfd 8*\nDominion Iron A Steel 18%\nEdison Electric Ilium 209\nGenera! Electric 122\nMasvaehusetta Electric 10\nMassachusetts Electric pfd 4t>\ni !aassachusettb lias Ki\nUnited Fruit 141\nj United Shoe Machine 55%\nUnited Shoe Machine pfd 27%\nI\". S. Steel.. 27\nU. S. Steel pfd 101%\ntflVIVll\nAdventure 2\nAllouez 27\nAmalgamated HttTi\n1 Atlantic 15\nBingham ^jO\nCalumet Hecla H70\nCentennial 234\nCopier Range 71'?\nItaly H'fst K'Va\nFranklin, bid W\ntirauby. asked 1004\nIsle Roy ale li?4\nMassachusetts Mining 4\nMichigan 8%\nMohawk. bid HI\nMontana Coal t Coke 4.7\nOld Dominion :-t4*^j\ni*?\nI'arrot. bid 22\nQuincy 84\nShannon 13-4\nTamarack 57\nTrinity 13\nI'nited Copper 7\nI nited Slates Mining .\".7U,\nCnited States oil 25\nUtah 42\nVictoria 5\nWinona 54\nWolverine 131)\ni MANCHESTER CLOTH MARKET.\nMANCHESTER. June 13.?Business on\nthe cloth market was at a standstill this\nt week owing to the action of manufactur\nera In closing down the mills for the\nwhole of Whltsun week.\na IN 1\n[E WORLD\nTHE FOREIGN MARKETS.\nLONDON. June 13.?The activity on the\nstock exchange slackened this week in all\ndepartments. The early strength was replaced\nby a sagging tendency, which left\nvalues generally lower on the week.\nThe settlement absorbed much attention\nand revealed the bull account open, and\nwhen the various loan operations were\nprojected, including the borrowings of Brazil\nand Sweden, as well as of the various\nhome corporations, dealers promptly took\ntheir profits, especially in the home rail\nand Kaffir sections of the market, while\nselling by Berlin weakened foreigners at\nho\nIUC CIIU U1 lll?= V*cciv. jr iuaj raw voosat\nion of this selling, however, and with\nsome covering operations the markets improved\nonly to droop again in sympathy\nwith American securities.\nThe business in American rails is still\nshrinking, and the market/here gets little\nencouragement. The cut in steel prices\nand rumors of receiverships checked local\nenthusiasm, but with small offerings and\nmoderate professional support values were\nheld up until Friday, when the announcement\nregarding the Erie coupon interest\ncaused a pronounced weakness, which\ncontinued today. Values, however, finished\nabove the lowest.\nOn the week prices ranged from par to\n2 points lower. Erie was an exception,\nbeing 5 points down, but it closed stead-\nier.\nPARIS. June 13.?Trading on the bourse j\ntoday strengthened after an early show\nof weakness.\nBERLIN, June 13.?Trading on the\nbourse today was very weak on New\nYork advices. j\nNEW YORK BANK STATEMENT, i\n1\nNEW YORK. June 13.?The statement\nof clearing house banks for the week\nshows that the banks hold $53,481,300\nmore than the requirements of the 25-percent-reserve\nrule. This is an increase of\n$6,199,100 in the proportionate cash reserve\nas compared with previous accounts\nThe statement follows:\nLoans, $1,213,866,600; increase. $2,264,700.\nDeposits, $1,289,256,400; increase, $6,756,000.\nCirculation. $56,634,400; decrease, $196,400.\nLegral tenders. $74,237,900; increase.\n$2,365,900.\nSpecie. $301,467,500; increase, $5,522,200.\nReserve, $375,705,400; increase, $7,888.100.\nReserve required, $322,314,100; Increase,\n$1,709,000.\nSurplus. $53,481,300; increase, $6,199,100\nEx United States deposits, $58,439,400;\nincrease. $6,199,225.\nThe percentage of actual reserve of the\nclearing house banks at the close of business\nyesterday was 29.59.\nThe statement of banks and trust companies\nof Greater New York not members\nof the clearing house shows that\nthese institutions have aggregate deposits\nof $950,664,400; total cash on hand. $72,166,900,\nand loans amounting to $892,550,200.\nMoney on call, nominal. Time loans.\neasy; 60 days 2. and no days 2Vi per ceni;\nsix months. 3% per cent.\nClose: Prime mercantile paper. 3% to 4 1\nper cent. Sterling exchange steady, with\nactual business in bankers' bills at 4.S6.80a\n4.8685 for demand, and at 4.8525a4.S535\nfor sixty-day bills. Commercial bills.\n4 85a4.85%. Bar silver, 53%. Mexican dollars.\n47. Government bonds steady. Railroad\nbonds steady.\nThe Financier says:\nThe statement of the associated banks\nof New York city for the week ending\nSaturday showed a very substantial increase\nIn all principal items, the cash\ngain alone having been $10,706,500, which\ncorresponds rather closely with the pre-\nliminary estimate made earlier in the\nweek.\nThe blinks increased their loans $8,-\n453.100. probably as a result of some of\nthe public bond offerings of the week,\nbut deposits increased only $13,239,800.\nwhich is less by several million dollars\nthan ought to have been shown by the J\nchanges already noted. The banks are\nstill gaining largely from the interior.\nThey are gaining also in their operations\nwith the subtreasury, and as the exports\nof gold during the week were inconse-\nquential, the loss on this account was\nsmall. 1\nIt is noticeable, however, that the trust\ncompanies are increasing tneir casn very\nrapidly, this being due, as was pointed i\nout last week, to the fact that the law\nrequires them on July 1 to maintain a\nheavier reserve of cash in their own i\nvaults rather than in the form of deposits\nwith other banks and trust companies.\nFor the week just ended the state banks\nand trust companies not reporting to the\nNew York clearing house gained $4,269,9C0\ncash, almost wholly in specie.\nThe trust companies and state banks\nalso report a heavy increase of $11,331,700\nin loans and $15,296,500 in net deposits,\nthese changes being due probably to financial\noperations incident to the offering of\na large series of railway bonds, which\ncame on the market last week. The increase\nin the associated bank reserves\nfor the week was $7,390,550. and the total\nsurplus reserve, including those on public\ndeposits, is now $56,677,275.\nThe reduction in actual reserves since\nMay 9 last, when the first decreases in\nthis item were noted, had been up to the\nbeginning of May about $11,000,000, which,\nconsidering the constant exports of gold,\nthe repayments of public deposits and the\nwithdrawals of public deposits by the\ntreasury, indicates how far the movement\nfrom tlie interior has gone to counteract\nthe heavy withdrawals mentioned.\nTO RESTRAIN THE NEW HAVEN.\nWrit Asked to Prevent Voting of\nB. and M. Stock.\nBOSTON. June 13.?A writ of injunction\nto restrain the New York. New Haven\nand Hartford railroad from voting\nstock of the Boston and Maine railroad\nor exercising any control over that corporation\nwas asked for by Attorney General\nMalcr.c in an information in equity\nfiled with the supreme judicial court to\nday.\nIn his petition the attorney general\nstates that he files the information at the\nrelation of State Commissioner of Corporations\nD. P. Trefry. me petition\nstates that the New Haven road has\nacquired and is now holding certain\nshares of stock in the Boston and Maine\nrailroad, a Massachusetts corporation, in\ndirect violation of law and against public\npolicy.\nI'nder the authority of a section of the\nstatutes which provides that the supreme\njudicial court shall have power to restrain\nby injunction any ccu-poratlon from\nassuming or exercising any franchise or\ntTJI nSar?tinor omr Kucina^o n r\\t ant\nJj cm J UUOKICOO J1V/L nuvitvi IWU\nby the charter of such corporation or by\nthe laws of the commonwealth, the petition\nprays that a writ of injunction be\nissued restraining the New Haven corporation\nfrom further use and enjoyment\nof the franchise and from directly taking,\nholding, controlling or voting Boston and\nMaine stock.\nNEW YORK IMPORTS.\nNEW YORK, June 13.?Imports of merchandise\nand dry goods at the port of\nNew York for the week ending June 1\nwere valued at $12,905,052.\nImports of specie for the port of New\nYork for the week ending today were $47,114\nsilver and $11,930 gold.\nExports of specie from the port of New\nYork for the week ending today were\n$754,030 silver and $1,702,800 gold.\nNEW YORK DRY GOODS.\nNEW YORK. June 13?Quietness prevails\nin the dry goods market, but prices\nare steady and the undertone is firm.\nSpecial offerings of summer merchandise\nwill be made by the Jobbers during the\ncoming week. Jobbers are holding their\nstaple merchandise firmer. Dress linens\nare quiet.\nA very large order of crested linens\n1 has recently been placed here by a Belfast\nmill. Burlaps are quiet, but more\ninquiry is noted for heavies by western\npeople.\nHE A E DON'CHANGE\nThe scope of supervision conferred a\n:he last session of Congress upon the in\n:erstate commerce commission over th<\nstreet railways of the District is conflnec\n:o the regulation of schedules and of th<\nstructural fitness of cars. The commis\nsion is given power to determine hov\nnany and how often and what sort of cars\nshall be run on any line.\nUnlike similar grants in recent years o\nlegislative jfbwer to commissions in somi\nstates, notably in New York and Wiscon\nson. Congress did not include within th<\nrange of this law any jurisdiction over th<\nfinances of the companies. In event an:\nadditional power is needed, either to issui\nstocks or bonds, it still would be neces\nsary to go to Congress.\nTherefore this new law is one of lim\nited powers and retains what some migh\nregard as the most essential of the powers\nwhich could be vested in the suprenv\ni ntVi\nXUIUU1 IIJ.\nIt is the second attempt on the part o\nCongress in this species of lawmaking\nit follows, at a long interval, the law o\nLS96. by which authority was conferral\nupon the Supreme Court of the Distric\nto determine upon examination into thi\ni-alue of the property of the gas compan;\nwhat increase in the capital stock wouli\nbe Just and fair.\nFor a long time the gas company di<\nnot avail Itself of this opportunity to se\n:ure the much-wanted privilege of in\nttreasing its capital stock. Finally appli\nfation was made to the court. An inquir\nwas made through the auditor of the cour\nind his finding approved.\nThe Court of Appeals, however, se\niside the action of the lower court on th\nground that the law was unconstitutional\nAppeal has been taken to the Suprenn\nCourt of the United States, where it stil\nis. Hearing is expected some time befor\nthe close of the current year.\nHowever, that is the extent of the at\n:empt on the part of Congress to delegat\niny of its powers over local corporations\nThe operation of the present law, especial\nly in the light of what seems to be th'\nJ 1 1\nkttvuviu tciiucMt.j' luwaiu d commisbioi\nform of government for corporations, wil\noe watched with considerable interest.\nIn the exercise of such powers as hav<\naeen granted to the interstate commero\n:ommission it is pointed out there is t\n:hance of both corporations and publi\njetting better acquainted with each other\nit may be expected that when the com\nulssion is asked by the citizens to compe\niny road to increase the number of car\njr to do anything in the way of changfni\nts service that would Involve additions\n:ost to the company, it would be neces\n?ary. for intelligent action on the part o\n:he commission, to know something of th\ninancial condition of the company. Ii\n:his way, while the commission has no\njower to regulate the issue or the amoun\n)f the securities of the company, yet i\n:an be the medium of getting informatioi\nibout finances.\nTn Kic CAiinoollori U\n1 fcitto v.uniiv\\-tivii 11 tua jr uc oaiu ma\nx?th street railway\" companies in this cit;\nire looked upon as in a position to stam\ni full and complete inquiry of this sort\nrhat opinion is based upon the past rec\njrds of the companies.\nIn the case of the Washington Railwa;\nind Electric Company, the largest ii\npoint of capitalization and of trackage, i\nPas recently passed from the control of\nnoting trust into the hands of the stock\nPolders. That change has been made with\n5ut disclosing anything in the manage\nment of the previous five years, whic\nlid not serve to strengthen the faith an\nthe belief of the new directors in th\npresent worth and the future of the prop\nerties.\nThe confidence in the other company i\nsolidly based on its achievements in th\nway of paying good returns to stockhold\nera and in a belief in its honest and capa\nble management.\nWashington Stock Exchange.\nSales.?Regular call, 12 o'clock noon?Caplt:\nTraction 3s. $1,000 at 110.\nWashington R?r. and lClec. nfd.. 10 at SO.\nWashington Gas. 25 at 05%, 1 at 65%.\nMergenthaler Linotype, 5 at 197%.\nGAS BONDS.\nBid. Aske<\nWashington Gas 4s 99% 103\nWashington Gas cert. 6s 100\nRAILROAD BONDS.\nCapital Traction 5s 109% 1111\nAuacostla and Potomac 3s 98\nCity and Suburban 5s 100\nColumbia 5a 102104\nColumbia Os 106%\nMetropolitan 5s 10S\nWashington Rwy. and Elec. 4s... 79% SO1\nMISCELLANEOUS BONDS.\nPotomac Electric Light 5s 103% 105\nNor. and Wash. Steamboat 5s.... 105\nChesapeake and Potomac Tel. 5s. 103% 107!\nWashington Market 5s. 1927 107\nWaahington Market 5s, 1947 107\nPUBLIC UTILITY STOCKS.\nCapital Traction 123 12G\nWashington Rwy. and Elec. com.. 29 31'\nWashington Rwy. and Elec. pld.. 79 S2\nNor. and Wash. Steamboat 260 500\nWashington Gas 65% OS\nGeorgetown Gas 62 SO\nBell Telephone of Pa 99 100\nTYPE MACHINE STOCKS.\nMergenthaler Linotype 197 19S:\nLanatou Monotype 9% 11\nMINING STOCKS.\nGreene Cananea 9% 10'\nMitchell\nNATIONAL BANK STOCKS.\nAmerican 165 ISO\nCapital 176\nCity 140 150\nUoluinbltt 275\nCommercial 173 102\nFarmers and Mechanics' 31-1\nLincoln 125\nMetropolitan 23?>\nRlggs 505\nSecond 141% 155\nWashington 380 407\nTUUST COMPANY STOCKS.\nAmerican Security ami Trust.... glt> 2g5\nNational Sate log goo\nUnion Trust Ill ll?\nWashington Loan and Trust 160 loo\nU. S. Trust 04 Vi 90\nSAVINGS BANK STOCKS.\nHome Savings goO 350\nMerchants and Mechanics' Savings 140 105\nUnion Savings g55 gTo\nFIKE 1NSUKANCK STOCKS.\nArlington g7 32\nColumbia 10 11\nCommercial 6\nCorcoran 74\nFiremen's 19 21\nFranklin 54\nGerjnar.-American 207 300\nMetropolitan S5\nNational Union 0\nPeople's 0 8\nPotouiuc g?\nBiggs 714 6\nTITLE INSURANCE STOCKS.\nColumbia 3l4\nlteal Estate Su\nMISCELLANEOUS STOCKS.\nGraphoplione com 30\nGrapbophoue pfd 00\nMerchants' Transfer snd Storage, lit)\nSecurity Storage 175\nWashington Market 10%\nCONDITION OF THE TREASURE\nThe condition of the Treasury at th\nbeginning of business yesterday was a\nfollows:\nReserve fund, gold coin and bullioi\n$150.000.000; trust funds, to redeem oui\nstanding certificates, gold coin, $S19,723\n869; silver dollars. $473,791,000; silver do\nlars of 1890, $5,029,090; total. $1,298,543\n869. General fund, $191,233,972; deposit\nin national banks, $108,171,007; in Philij\npine treasury, $3,203,800; awaiting reirr\nbursement, $22,021; current liabilitie;\n$122,770,369.\nSaturday's statement of the Treasur\nbalances In the general fund, exclusive\nthe $15u,000,00n gold reserve, shows\nAvailable cash balance, $239,862,331; go]\ncoin and bullion, $30,656,841; gold certif\ncates, $32,182,000.\nMIDSHIPMEN'S SUMMER CRUIS!\nPractice Base Changed From th\nRoads to New London.\nAfter careful consideration of all th\nconditions, climatic and others, it ha\nbeen decided by the Navy Department t\nchange the base of the Naval Academ\npractice squadron from Hampton road\nVa.. to New London, eonn. The practic\nsquadron, which has on board about 6*\nmidshipmen from the Naval Academy i\nAnnapolis, consists of the Olympia, tl\nChicago, the Hartford, the Arkansas an\nthe Nevada.\nIt was deemed advisable by the author\nties of the Navy Department to chang\nthe base because it was felt it would t\nbetter for the midshipmen to be for tl\nsummer in a climate different from th.\nat Hampdon roads, which substantial]\nis the same as that at Annapolis. Tl\nchange was decided upon after a consu\ntation between Secretary Metcalf and Ai\nsistant Secretary Newberry. The ordei\nhave not been issued yet, but the squac\nron will have its base at New Londc\nafter the 22d instant.\nIt matters little what it is that yc\nwant?whether a situation or a servant\na \"want\" ad in The Star will reach tl\nperson who can fill your need.\nFinancial News Letter 1\nBY W. O. NICHOLAS.\nSpecial Correspondence of The Star.\nNEW YORK. June 13. 1008\nThe stock market went deadly dull almost\nover night. Sales dropped from a\nmillion shares a day to around 2?*>.000\nshares. The difference represented in\ns large part the strictly manipulative feature\nof tl^e trading When the big leaders\ndrew out and left the market alone the\ns volume of business dwindled into comparative\nnothingness Wash trading and\ng matched orders, which have been a disP\ngraceful part of the manipulation for the\ne last ten weeks, disappeared entirely.\ngreatly to the disappointment of the twodollar\nbrokers who handle the bulk of\nt this sort of decoy business.\nThe sharp slump in the aggregate of\ne transactions has produced slight change\nin prices, fluctuation going on about as\nf before, one day up and the next day oft.\nwith nothing in the proceedings to indif\ncate a trend, unless it be that values ini\nclined to sag a little when left alone. Apt\nparently the good things in the situation\ne have been to a large extent discounted,\ny and the market is in a mood to await furi\nther political and trade developments before\nmaking a decided start up or down.\n3\n\nUnquestionably the near approach of\nthe national convention Is the chief cont\ntributory cause of the present inaction.\nThe market masters appear quite willing\nt to hold off until they see who is nome\ninated at Chicago and have a chance to\ng study the platform. The selection of Mr.\n1 Taft as republican standard bearer is gene\nerally accepted as foreordained, but there\nare other things to be considered beside\nthat mere fact. It is regarded as of mare\nket importance to ascertain what kind of\na taste the convention leaves in the mouth\nof the public and whether or not irrecone\ncilable bitterances are engendered which\nn may weaken the ticket at the polls In ICo1\nvember. It is considered of the very highest\nimportance among the great Industrial\ne corporations as to the degree of tariff ree\nvision which may be foreshadowed in the\na platform. That there will be revision next\nvAa r nr the i a fnllA in tr ic conAr^llv\nL J v? kiiu jtai Bv>*V4\nconceded, a fact which is already having\ndecided market influence, remote though\nil the actual change may be.\ns It does not follow that even though the\nS republicans may retain control of the na.1\ntional House of Representatives by a\nsmall majority they will be able to pref\nvent sharp revision, for among the ree\npublicans of both branches of Congress\na there is and probably will be a%formldt\nable element llke*y to work with the demt\nocrats for a drastic reduction from- the\nt high protective schedules of today. The\nn New England membership In Congress\nis expected to give material aid In this\nt direction, a f^ct well understood in flnany*\ncial as well as political circles. The agld\ntatlon incident to anticipated tariff revision\ncan hardly fail to exert a depress\nlng Influence on stock quotations, espe-\ncially of the Iron and steel issues, sugar,\ny tobacco, paper, lead, leather, etc. The\nn great railroad equipment companies and\nt the electric companies will naturally be\na benefited by the cheapened cost of raw A\nmaterial. The railroads should also be\ni- the gainer from the increased tonnage\n/In a 4a n n Anlni'OA/1 t?oln*MA c.f Kit cinACC\nuuc iu ait cuiai 5CU vuiuiur ui\nh This latter point is urged strongly by the s\nd tariff reformers; it Is. in fact, one of the\ne main points. And then comes another\n1- intensely disturbing factor?disturbing to\nbusiness and politics alike?the inevitable\ns readjustment of wages which must fol-\nlow important tariff reduction. X\nAll of these things are already in the\nminds of men who have to look ahead\nand plan for the management of the vast X\ninterests entrusted to them. They are f>\nalso in the minds of those dependent upon\ncorporation earnings for their living?the\n11 stockholders and bondholders, who now\nnumber more than 1,000,000. t\n\n\nThe revival in business, while perceptl- J\\\nble. has not yet assumed anything like\nthe proportions of a boom, much as the ff\nmembers of the Sunshine Club would like\nto have it appear that way. It is prob-\nably true that the shelves of the mer- 4\nchants throughout the country are not\noverstocked, and that the warehouses of 1\nVa manufacturers and wholesalers are far J\nfrom glutted, yet purchasers of fresh supplies\nare as yet rather sparing. In mills and\nu factories and workshops and in the build-\ning and other trades the increased volume\nof orders finds reflection more in the\nlonger hours to employes kept on the j\nrolls than to the hiring of additional men.\nThis betokens a general lack of confidence\nin the wholesale return of prosperity and\nin the permanency of the improvement\nalready observable. The eiteot of the cut\nin steel and iron prices and in ore cannot\nyet.be measured. 't\nft There is a difference of opinion as to\nwhether the price reduction will stimulate\nbusiness or whether intending buyers will\nijj hold off for a further concession. The c\nresult of the action of the big combine k\nin yielding to the pressure for lower q\nprices is being awaited with very great ?j\ninterest. i\n1\nC\n<1\nThe aggregate of new corporation cap\nital during the first half of the current <i\nyear has been larger than most people J\ndream of. Since the 1st of January the i\nrailroads and industrial companies have 6:\nauthorized the sale of $203,000,000 in new\nstocks and $1,037,000,000 in new bonds. ?j\nagainst about $500,000,000 stocks and\n$030,000,000 bonds for the corresponding\nperiod of last year. The $>ig borrowers\nhave certainly made a heroic grab for\nloanable funds in sight. For the time\nbeing they seem to have got about all\nthey want, although ne.w flotations for\nmoderate amounts are coming out right\nalong, the latest being $13,000,000 in New\nYork Central debentures (notes) soon to\nbe distributed by Mr. Morgan's house, j\nThe ITnion Pacific made a success of its\n$50,000,000 bond flotation here and abroad,\nand Mr. Harriman is again flush with\nready cash to liquidate the immense U.\nVa P. floating indebtedness and continue his\npurchase of such other properties as he\nmay take a fancy to.\n\nIt took about four years to bring George\nGould to a realization that he was amen..\nable to discipline. He has at last learned\nhis lesson, however, admits the fact and\np\ngives pledge of his withdrawal from the\nfield of disturbance. He will hereafter\nlf* be a good boy if he is allowed to retain\n3 control of his Missouri Pacific and\nWabash systems with their natural exi,\ntensions and allies. He died hard, and it\nt_ was only when brought face to face with\nthe cold hard fact that If he did not\nlisten to reason and advice he would be\nthoroughly isolated and backed off the\nboards eventually. As it is he lias\ng formed a truce with Mr. Harriman under\nthe terms of which he will be allowed 1\nto complete the Western Pacific to San i\nl\" Francisco. He must, however, abandon\ns. his ambitius plans for an eastern ex- j\ntension from Pittsburg to Baltimore,\ny\n>f i\nA well defined rumor is in circulation\nthat Morgan Co. are behind a project i\nfor the consolidation of a number of the i\nleading automobiling manufacturing com\nE parries The combine is said to be inter- i\nnational in its character and imposing in\ne the volume of capitalization. It is an open i\nsecret tliat a great many of these com-\npanies are in a bad way. and therefore,\nle in just the mood to lend willing ear to\nls the gospel of consolidation.\na\n\ny The speed with which the government i\ns. and the banks are getting ready for the 1\n?e issuance of $.?00.000.0<K> emergency cur-\n)0 rency next fall should\" there be need for\nit it is cheering to the Wall street speculate\ntors. With that amount of money on tap\nl(j there will probably be no need for its\nactual distribution, but if there should it\nwill surely be handed out. Most con-\nservative bankers seem to be of the\ne opinion that the business revival will not\n>e have progressed sufficiently to require an\nle artificial Inflation of stocks to require an i\nsupply crop moving and other demands, j\nly In other words, they think there will be\n>e enough to go around naturally and legit'*\nimately. They do not anticipate a spons\"\ntaneous and wholesale return to antics\npanic prosperity. i\n1- c\nin ma\nThe showing made by the harvester\ntrust on the occasion of its application to\nhave its stocks listed on the stock ex-\nchange was a revelation to most people.\nThi