is it\nwith a steadily increasing surplus enables\nt to carry a stock of about $o0.00u.b0??.\nipen accounts with customers of about\n5W.O0O.OtiO and to engage in several lines rt\n)f profitable business incidental to the if\nnanufacture and sale of harvester and j je\n>ther farm machinery. The big Harvester y\nTompany will come in for vicious political, Ji\nittack during the coming summer and fall\nm account of the active part it is taking 2\nn the campaigns of several western and\nlorthwestern states where it seeks to con- 5\nrol the election of state legislators. ifr\ncongressmen and governors, it is also in- j\nciting trouble later on when Congress gtis\niown to the work of tariff revision.\ni\ni\nThe governors of the stock exchange are\nengaged just now in a campaign of self- j y8\npurification. They have been moved to\nio this by the scandalous exposure of dis- j Jg\nlonest practices by prominent and active j nembers\nrecently forced into bankruptcy. J\nr- oVvAnt fnr Ci-?onAprna tc I hpv J41*A 4\nL II lUUIVilig ClUUWt iV/4 ...V^\nikely to find some conspicuous members j\nwho have been flagrant violators of some i.\n3f the rules of the exchange. One of the\nabuses complained of is that of beating\nIke state out of transfer stamps on stock\nsales.\nSecret bucket shopping is also to be\nstamped out and punishment meted to\nthose who have illicit dealings with the\nconsolidated and other local exchanges.\nThe stock exchange governors have these\nspasms of virtue once every three or four\nyears. They usually land two or three\n\"goats.\" and then apply the gooa om j\nwhitewash in the good old way. And then J\nthe shearing of the lambs proceeds as J\nusual.\n\nProposals Asked for Steam Colliers.\nJuly 1 the Navy Department will open\nbids for three new steam colliers to be j\nconstructed by the authority of a recent\nact of Congress. The ships must be abla\nto carry 7.200 tons of dead weight and\ncost not to exceed $525,000 each. The\nproposals provide that the vessels shall be\nturned over to the government complete\nin every respect and ready for sea duty.\nLieut. Shiras Dies at Manila.\nThe insular bureau of the War Depart-\nment is notified by cable from Manila\nof the death of Fred D. Shiras of rheumatism\nof the heart. Mr. Shiras was a lieutenant\nin the 45th Volunteer Infantry, y!\nand on the muster-out of that regiment i\nwas appointed senior inspector in the J\nPhilippine constabulary. His home was\nin Dubuque, Iowa.\nFINANCIAL.\nAND SURPLUS, 52.200,000\niw Interest\nmjpany's hanking department\neposits subject to check.\nupervision of\nDepartment.\nCOMPANY.\nd H Streets.\nKdson B. OMs............ Treasurer\nMarry O. Wilson AMM.-tanf Truaur.r\nVV. Frank P. Herr n Auditor\nEdward L. Hlllyer.. Ax'Utant Secretary\n;?TY BANK,\nreet N.W.\nBail Account? I\nif\nthis bank your depository. It\nequipped in every manner to \\j\nand pleasant. p\ncounts of firms, corporations jjj\nPresident ~tf\nVice Pres. and Cashier\nAsst. Cashier\nORS. t\nte1x. james o donnell.\nJ. h. ralston.\nr. FRED B RHODES. r\nrtle. r. t. sanner\nIN. Jr.. H. WTNVHiP wjjf.atley.\n8. W. WOODWARD\nJ\n-W\nCapital. $1.0>M).00n?Surplus. $1..* <>.otjt?.\njyp^ortey Transmitted\nilM BY CABLE.\nDrafts issued direct on principal\ncities of the world.\nT Cr-+A\\f icciipH\nL#tlIV. 1 3 Ul V* vuti. UJUVU.\nExchange bought and sold.\nInvestments Collections made.\nStocks and Bonds bought sold.\nRIGOS Sank.*'\npa. .we orrosiTi: u. s. treasury\nMoney at 5%\nloaned 6x d.*c. heal estate.\nHeiskell McLeran.\nMSMf 1-503 M sr\nUnder U. S. Treasury Supervision.\nMake the 1\nStart.\nSaving is a iiabit that has g\nto be acquired. The easiest\nway is to start a savings account\nand then make up your\nmind to add something to it\neach week. Start with as as\nsmall an account as you like,\nbut start.\n_\nHome Savings Bank,?\n7th and Mass. Ave. N.W.\nBRANCHES:\n7th and H Sts. N.E.\n436 7th St. SAW\nlOlS-tf r.?\nm-I-X\"!\":-!\"!-: 11 1;: 1:\nOrganized E879. t\nAssets, $2,249,405.09.\nTHE